text:
Among all the discourse that surrounds the NBA, most people tend to overlook the bench players. But they do matter, right? I mean, why else would the NBA have a Sixth Man of the Year award? A lot of people might say that having a deep bench is important for winning championships, while others will say that an All-Star starting five is what matters. So let’s figure out just how important bench players are in the NBA.
One of the most important things a bench player can do is come into the game and help produce points. To do this, we are going to be looking at the past 20 seasons of NBA basketball and see how many points that bench players contributed. We will be using hoopR to pull the total points scored by bench players since 2005.
The first question that we’ll ask is how bench scoring has changed over the course of 20 years. So here is what has changed.


Code
library(tidyverse)
library(hoopR)
library(gt)

nba_player_stats &lt;- read_csv("data/nba_player_stats.csv")

team_stats &lt;- read_csv("data/team_stats.csv")

bench_points &lt;- nba_player_stats |&gt;
  filter(starter == FALSE) |&gt;
  filter(did_not_play == FALSE) |&gt;
  group_by(team_name) |&gt;
  summarise(total_bench_points = n()) |&gt;
  filter(total_bench_points &gt;= 6000) |&gt;
  arrange(desc(total_bench_points))

bench_points_over_time &lt;- nba_player_stats |&gt;
  filter(starter == FALSE) |&gt;
  filter(did_not_play == FALSE) |&gt;
  group_by(season) |&gt;
  summarise(total_bench_points = n()) |&gt;
  filter(total_bench_points &gt;= 6000) |&gt;
  arrange(desc(total_bench_points))

team_wins &lt;- team_stats |&gt;
  filter(team_winner == TRUE) |&gt;
  group_by(team_name) |&gt;
  summarise(total_wins = n()) |&gt;
  filter(total_wins &gt;= 450) |&gt;
  arrange(desc(total_wins))

logs &lt;- left_join(team_wins, bench_points)

ggplot() + geom_line(data=bench_points_over_time, aes(x=season, y=total_bench_points)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(
    y = "Season",
    x = "Total Bench Points",
    title = "A Big Change",
    subtitle = "Bench point production dropped significantly after 2011 and has not risen since.",
    caption = "Source: SportsDataVerse | By Nick Clark"
  )+
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(size = 18, face = "bold"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 10),
    axis.title = element_text(size = 8),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
  )









So clearly, we are living in a different era of basketball than in the late 2000s and early 2010s. Since that time, bench players haven’t been contributing as much to a team’s scoring. This means that more load is put on starters to score most, if not all, of a team’s points during the course of a season. Which shouldn’t come as too much of a surprise, given that there are stars in the NBA capable of putting up 40 points a game consistently.
But does that mean bench players don’t contribute to a team’s success? Is there a connection between the number of bench points scored and the number of games a team wins?


Code
ggplot() +
  geom_point(data = logs, aes(x=total_wins, y=total_bench_points)) +
  geom_smooth(data = logs, aes(x=total_wins, y=total_bench_points), method = "lm", color = "red") +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(
    y = "Bench Points",
    x = "Wins",
    title = "A good bench makes the difference",
    subtitle = "Over 20 years, higher scoring benches mean more wins",
    caption = "Source: SportsDataVerse | By Nick Clark"
  ) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(size = 18, face = "bold"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 12),
    axis.title = element_text(size = 8),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank()
  )









This is interesting, isn’t it? Even though we’ve seen a steep drop-off in bench scoring production since the early 2010s, teams that have high-scoring benches are still winning more than their competition. So even if the trend has changed, the truth hasn’t.
But which teams do this the best? Over the past 20 years, which teams in the NBA have had the highest scoring benches every year? And are those teams successful? Meaning did they have deep playoff runs or win a championship? Let’s find out.


Code
season_rankings_data &lt;- nba_player_stats |&gt;
  filter(starter == FALSE) |&gt;
  filter(did_not_play == FALSE) |&gt;
  group_by(team_name, season) |&gt;
  summarise(season_bench_points = n()) |&gt;
  arrange(desc(season_bench_points))

top_bench &lt;- season_rankings_data |&gt;
  select(team_name, season, season_bench_points) |&gt;
  mutate_at(vars(-team_name), as.numeric) |&gt;
  group_by(team_name) |&gt;
  rename(Team = team_name) |&gt;
  rename(BenchPointsScored = season_bench_points) |&gt;
  rename(Season = season) |&gt;
  select(Team, BenchPointsScored, Season) |&gt;
  arrange(desc(BenchPointsScored)) |&gt;
  ungroup()

top_bench_new &lt;- top_bench |&gt; top_n(wt = BenchPointsScored, n = 10)

top_bench_new |&gt;
  gt() |&gt;
  cols_label(
    BenchPointsScored = "Bench Points"
  ) |&gt;
  tab_header(
    title = "Teams that represent a bygone era of basketball",
    subtitle = "The Heat had the highest scoring benches in recent history before losing to the Mavericks in the Finals, who also had a high scoring bench."
  ) |&gt; tab_style(
    style = cell_text(color = "black", weight = "bold", align = "left"),
    locations = cells_title("title")
  ) |&gt; tab_style(
    style = cell_text(color = "black", align = "left"),
    locations = cells_title("subtitle")
  ) |&gt;
  tab_source_note(
    source_note = md("**By:** Nick Clark | **Source:** hoopR: The SportsDataverse's R Package for Men's Basketball Data")
  ) |&gt;
  tab_style(
     locations = cells_column_labels(columns = everything()),
     style = list(
       cell_borders(sides = "bottom", weight = px(3)),
       cell_text(weight = "bold", size=12)
     )
     ) |&gt;
  tab_style(
    style = list(
      cell_fill(color = "#98002E"),
      cell_text(color = "white")
      ),
    locations = cells_body(
      rows = Team == "Heat")
  )








